# Dashboard service dependencies — HUMAN-EDITED SOURCE (pip-tools input).
#
# This lists the dashboard's *direct* deps as version ranges. The installable,
# fully-pinned lockfile is the GENERATED `dashboard/requirements.txt` (every
# transitive dep pinned to an exact version) — that is what CI and Railway install.
#
# Editing flow:
#   1. edit THIS file (add / loosen / tighten a direct dep)
#   2. regenerate the lock:
#        python3.10 -m piptools compile dashboard/requirements.in \
#            --output-file dashboard/requirements.txt
#   3. commit BOTH files in the same change
#
# Why a lockfile: ranges let a fresh CI/Railway install resolve to a brand-new
# release that breaks us — the httpx 0.28 break (2026-06-19) is the worked example.
# Pinning the full closure makes installs reproducible.
#
# NOTE — deliberately NO `--generate-hashes`: CI installs this alongside the bot's
# (unhashed) root `requirements.txt` in a single `pip install` command, and pip's
# hash-checking mode is all-or-nothing. Hashes arrive with the bot lock (the 2nd PR
# of the Q-0177 lock plan), when the install can be split.
#
# Kept separate from the bot's root requirements.txt so CI's bot install and the
# bot's Railway build are unaffected (the dashboard is a separate Railway service).

fastapi>=0.139.0,<1.0
uvicorn[standard]>=0.50.2,<1.0
jinja2>=3.1.6,<4.0
# httpx: the Discord OAuth token/identity calls + the bot control-API client, and
# the test suite's Starlette TestClient transport.
httpx>=0.28.1,<1.0
# NOTE: the OAuth login session is a small stdlib HMAC-signed cookie
# (dashboard/websession.py) and the editor forms are parsed with urllib
# (dashboard/app.py::_form) — deliberately NO itsdangerous / python-multipart, so
# the whole app stays verifiable with just fastapi + jinja2 + httpx installed.
